===Etymology===
From {{bor|en|la|acanthus}}, from {{der|en|grc|ἄκανθος}}, from {{m|grc|ἀκή||thorn}} + {{m|grc|ἄνθος||flower}}.<ref name=WI3>{{R:MW3 1976}}</ref><ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/əˈkæn.θəs/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/əˈkæn.θəs/}}
* {{rhymes|en|ænθəs}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|+|acanthi}}

# A member of the genus ''[[Acanthus]]'' of [[herbaceous]] [[prickly]] plants with toothed leaves, (family [[Acanthaceae]], order [[Lamiales]] (formerly {{taxlink|Scrophulariales|order|ver=210204}})) found in the south of Europe, Asia Minor, and India.{{defdate|First attested in the mid 16th century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1834|author={{w|Letitia Elizabeth Landon}}|title=Francesca Carrara|volume=1|pages=255-256|text=Francesca gazed upon it as if it had been an old friend: many a time, beside such a one, with its curved and broken marble, had she wreathed the '''acanthus''' that hung around it, the green and trailing foliage so profuse in the South, into shapes even more fanciful than those which once suggested the Corinthian capital.}}
#: {{syn|en|bear's breech|bear's breeches|bear's-breech|q3=rare}}
# {{lb|en|architectural element}} An ornament resembling the [[foliage]] or leaves of {{taxlink|Acanthus spinosus|species}}, used in the [[capital]]s of the [[Corinthian]] and [[composite]] orders.{{defdate|First attested in the mid 18th century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1994|month=March|work=Journal of the Society of Architectural Historians|title=Early Christian and Byzantine Architecture, an Annotated Bibliography and Historiography by W. Eugene Kleinbauer|author=R Ousterhout |volume=53|number=1|passage=It is difficult to imagine that Bernard of Clairvaux was gullible enough to accept dozens of historiated windows, grisaille fields of griffins, mosaic pavements, carved '''acanthus''' capitals, inhabited vine columns, and golden altarware on the strength of the justifications offered by a single window, one tympanum, and Suger's libelli}}

